The U.S. Anti-China Tech War
From New York — — The worst diplomatic policy decision made by the previous generation (and even earlier generations) of Americans was the 2003 "War of Choice" launched against Iraq, which claimed to aim at eliminating — — non-existent — — weapons of mass destruction.
Understanding the necessity of the flawed logic behind this disastrous decision has become more critical than ever, as the same logic is now being used to justify similar U.S. misleading policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into terrorist hands was small (such as 1%), we should act as if it were certain to happen.
This line of reasoning almost always leads to erroneous decisions.
However, the United States and some of its allies are now using Cheney's logic to attack Chinese technology.
According to the U.S. government's reasoning, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should treat it as definitely harmful and take action to ban it.
A correct decision would apply probability estimates to all alternative courses of action.
One generation ago, U.S. policymakers should not only have considered the (claimed) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into terrorist hands, but also the 99% risk of waging a war based on multiple flawed premises.
By focusing solely on that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) diverted public attention, leading people to overlook the fact that the Iraq War lacked justification and would severely destabilize Middle Eastern and global politics.
But the problem with Cheney's approach is not only that it forces action based on a small risk without considering the high potential costs, but also that politicians always stoke fear for some hidden purposes.
This is exactly what American leaders are doing again: highlighting and exaggerating certain small risks to incite panic about Chinese tech companies.
The most relevant (but not the only) case is the U.S. government's attack on the telecommunications company Huawei.
The U.S. is gradually closing its domestic market to the company and is trying to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the U.S. may ultimately cause an unfounded geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been closely following the technological advancements of Huawei, because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide great momentum for eliminating poverty and achieving other United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encouraged the industry to enhance actions towards the Sustainable Development Goals.
I once wrote a short introduction (without compensation) for a report that Huawei prepared on this topic, and as a result, I was criticized by those who are hostile towards China. I therefore asked senior industry executives and government officials if there was any evidence that Huawei had engaged in improper behavior, and the repeated answer I received was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment could endanger global security.
U.S. officials claim that the "backdoors" retained in Huawei's software or hardware could allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance globally.
They point out that China's laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are clear now.
Huawei's 5G equipment is affordable and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and has already started to be rolled out.
Its high performance comes from massive investments in R&D over the years, scale economy effects, and experience gained from operating in China's digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology for sustainable development, it would be clearly unwise for low-income economies around the world to delay the introduction of 5G.
However, despite lacking any evidence of backdoors, the U.S. is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
The U.S. argument is presented as universal.
As one U.S. Federal Communications Commissioner said: "The country with 5G will have the related innovation and set the standards for the rest of the world, and this country is unlikely to be the U.S. at the moment."
Other countries — especially the UK — have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software or hardware.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they are almost certainly able to be closed at that time.
The debate over Huawei is also raging in Germany, because the U.S. government threatens to cut intelligence cooperation unless the authorities exclude Huawei's 5G technology.
Perhaps under pressure from the U.S., the head of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement similar to Cheney's ideology: "Infrastructure is not a field that should be open to a group that cannot be fully trusted."
And he was unable to provide any evidence of specific wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel is quietly fighting to open the market to Huawei.
But ironically, the U.S. complaints partly reflect its own domestic and foreign surveillance activities — although this is no longer news.
Chinese equipment may make it more difficult for the U.S. government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any government's unlawful surveillance activities should be stopped.
Independent oversight by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecom system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards, rather than engage in a technological war.
The threatening impact of the U.S. demand to ban Huawei extends beyond the early rollout of 5G networks and also poses significant risks to the rule-based trading system.
Now the United States is no longer an unquestioned global technological leader, and President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete based on a rules-based system.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
They also attempt to undermine the World Trade Organization by paralyzing its dispute settlement mechanism, which similarly reflects their approach to global rules.
If the Trump administration successfully divides the world into different technological camps, the risk of future conflicts will double.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade, which not only improved global efficiency, expanded the U.S. technology market, but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
Part of the collapse was due to protectionist tariffs imposed by the United States under the 1930 Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act, which exacerbated the Great Depression and contributed to the rise of Hitler, ultimately leading to the outbreak of World War II.
As in other areas, inciting fear and taking action based on it — rather than following evidence — is a path toward destruction.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules; this is the safest approach.
Let us establish independent oversight bodies to reduce the threat of any country using the global network to monitor other countries or launch cyber warfare.
In this way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
